Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
Cambridge – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates huge profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
However, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the manner of preventing their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In the case of financial markets, an unexpected collapse in real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivatives and repo markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
While the underlying risks arise outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck ensured that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
A Fukushima, the workers are valiantly trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, the analogous efforts for derivatives are misdirected and will not prevent the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivative products and financial structures over the same errors that remain active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one party accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want yen risk, while another party will face the opposite.
In this case, the first party promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second party promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debts, against cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the following day (hence the term "repo," which is short for the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, ndt).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which means that even minor financial tremors can significantly impact them.
Some institutions may then find themselves without repo financing, as happened in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually, derivatives or repo transactions are not particularly blameworthy.
Each separately transfers risk legitimately to those who are best able to bear it, or allows financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can blow up the financial system due to their design flaws.
Today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of major American financial companies are composed of very short-term loans, such as those payable the following day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempt derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivatives or repo contracts with fragile financial institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. By doing so, they can decide its fate when, with a bit more time, the company might have survived.
Such actions destroyed AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos often have priority claims in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to promote market discipline by closely monitoring their counterparties' solvency and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be paid, anyway.
Of course, someone must be first.
<s>D'autres acteurs financiers doivent supporter plus de risque du fait que les exemptions des acteurs en produits dérivés et repo placent ces derniers en première ligne en cas de faillite.
<s>Normalement, on s’attendrait à ce que les autres aient donc un intérêt à encourager davantage de discipline de marché.
<s>Mais l'acteur qui suit dans la ligne est trop souvent le gouvernement américain, en tant que garant d'institutions financières « too-big-to-fail » (trop importantes pour les laisser faire faillite, ndt). Or, le gouvernement est mal placé pour réguler ces marchés au quotidien.
<s>Il n'est pas agile financièrement ; il se cantonne souvent au marché régulé ; et, lorsque les conditions économiques sont bonnes, aucun officiel ne voudrait gâcher la fête.
<s>Le Congrès américain a eu une opportunité de solutionner ce défaut dans le remaniement majeur de la finance qu'il a adopté l'été dernier via le projet de loi Dodd Frank.
But he did not take it.
<s>If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit events, ndt) did not benefit from favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
<s>First and foremost, they would insist more often on adequate capitalization of their counterparties.
<s>They accepted the risk of ultra-low capitalization when it came essentially to American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money at stake.
<s>The public perceives the risks of Fukushima differently from the risks associated with derivatives.
<s>Many people fear nuclear risks, which are stark, causing sectors facing security concerns to slow down.
<s>But the risks of derivatives and repos are misunderstood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
<s>During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
<s>Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami risks through passive cooling systems.
<s>It is now considered possible to build nuclear plants capable of keeping fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete power outage.
However, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damages that the priority of derivatives and repos in bankruptcy could cause in a new financial crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that final users (like oil companies using derivatives to protect against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak incentives for market discipline among the major financial institutions.
It's as if we were responding to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully transfer the risk related to their decisions to investors in derivatives and repos when they engage with systemic vital financial institutions.
AUTHOR'S NOTE: We have survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
